{
  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti chapter 1, verse 10, Manu provides a folk etymology for the name Nārāyaṇa in the context of cosmogony.**[^1]\n\nAfter the Self-Existent One casts his seed into the waters, which become a golden egg, Manu explains: \"The waters are called *nārāḥ*, for the waters are indeed the sons of Nara; and since they were his first dwelling place (*ayana*), he is therefore remembered as Nārāyaṇa.\"[^2]\n\nThis derives *Nārāyaṇa* from *nāra* ( waters, as offspring of Nara) + *ayana* (dwelling/movement/path), portraying the primordial waters as his initial abode.\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, ch. 1, [translation](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, ch. 1, [p-0bfa5b](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-0bfa5b).",
